title: For Sale:  1943 Type 99 Arisaka (Last Ditch model)
postcontent: This is a 1943 Type 99 "last ditch" Arisaka.  As a last ditch rifle, it doesn't have any of the cool guy Arisaka items like the aircraft sight, dust cover or monopod.  What is does have is a decent bore, intact wooden butt plate, decent action, and rudimentary sights made by genuine Japanese child slave labor.  The rifle is rough.  You can tell it was made by kids or others not skilled in the trade.  It's a part of history.  It would go nice with an earlier Type 99 to show the stark differences that an industry destroyed by war will make.  7.7 Jap is a bit hard to find so I haven't had a chance to shoot it.  I'm pretty sure a reloader could get the dies and make brass from 30-06 if so desired.  I just wanted it as a wall hanger.

~Cerakote Micro Slick is a dry-film lubricant that is able to withstand high temperatures and extreme pressures. The Micro Slick coating is able to lubricate, resist wear, and also act as an anti-seize agent while preventing galvanic corrosion or bonding of the metals.  Micro Slick is virtually unaffected by temperatures ranging from below zero to 1200 degrees Fahrenheit. When two adjoining surfaces are coated with Micro Slick it prevents surface-to-surface contact, which reduces friction and wear between the two surfaces. An example of this would be to coat a bolt carrier group on an AR 15 and the inside of the upper receiver. This combination would reduce the amount of friction between the parts and help the firearm to function more smoothly.

Micro Slick out-performs its competitors, such as Nickel Boron (NiB-X), Fail Zero, NP3, Titanium Nitride, etc. Because of this, Micro Slick is not only used on firearms, it is used on high performance vehicles as well, including vehicles in NASCAR.

title: For Trade:  1860 us Calvary saber from civil war trade for pistol
postcontent:
Very rare and sought after date Up for trade is my 1860 US cavalry saber with scabbard..not a reproduction, but the real McCoy , there were only 1200 of these made. I got it at an estate sale from a guy who dad died and was selling all his possessions ...the sword Weighing just under four pounds, the slightly curved blade measures 35" long with a width of 1 1/16", a 27½" wide fuller and a 19" long narrow fuller. Blade has stamping in a four-line Ames Company mark. Markings read "Made by / AMES MFG. CO. / CHICOPEE / MASS" with all letters within a scroll pattern. Obverse ricasso has stamped "U. S. / J.T. (?)/ 1860" stamp. Look at my pictures and you can see it..there's some rusty stuff covering up the lettering but it's there.. I'm not going to but steel wool would remove it to show the stamping..I used photo editing to show stamp ting better ..I did noting to refurbish it it is as I bought it...The steel blade exhibits scattered areas of dark, age discoloration and pinprick rust pitting overall. Blade wears a pleasing, dusky gray patina and appears to have there are some nicks on the blade but not to bad. Brass retains a dark mellow, bronze patina with some surface grime and nick and scratches on it overall. The center-swell wooden handle is covered with original black bridle leather and thin, double twisted brass wire wound around the grips. Leather wraps are peeling and show it age..hope pics are clear enough .Brass wire tight and in fine condition. Cavalry saber exhibits a brass pommel cap in the Phrygian design, common on all M1860 sabers. Pommel brim has no inspector marks visible.

Strong, steel scabbard is unadorned and has acquired a dark, almost plum colored patina with scattered areas of old rust pitting overall. A good steel wool would do wonders I bet, but in not going to.Sword mounts are tight and retain the original suspension sword rings. Steel scabbard shows three or four small dents overall. I read that the soldier carrying the sword would put dents on purpose in the scabbard to help keep the sword from rattling when moving..there's scattered spots of old rust pockmarking. Scabbard had no inspector stamp. Starting this auction at one buck! Any questions please ask
Also email or text me for more pics 614556766six
History update
This well-used specimen is a classic Civil War Federal edged weapon that was referred to as the "light cavalry saber" by the US Ordnance Department. Saber is one of those rare, early Ames contract, pre-Civil War Model 1860 cavalry pieces stamped "1860. 1,200 Model 1860 light cavalry sabers contracted in 1859 were shipped south to Virginia on orders from then Secretary John B. Floyd, himself a Virginian. Blades were all stamped with 'US' inspector marks and dated '1860
